default2.) defaultProgress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and social care services.default&#xa0;
default2.1
default 
defaultThe
default increase in demand for NHS eye care services 
defaultrequires
default careful planning by all health and social care professionals in order to slow, or even to halt, this rise. 
defaultSome progress has been made with 
defaultthe establishment of Local Eye Health Networks (LEHNs) across all NHS England Local Areas. 
default&#xa0;default2.2
default defaultThe aim is that
default these
default LEHNs will bring together all local eye health stakeholders in a clinically-led, patient- and population-focussed model to achieve progre
defaultss against the sight loss indicator locally. This will involve assessing local eye health needs, redesigning pathways as necessary in line with QIPP
default 
defaultprinciples and maximising the deployment of resources across primary, secondary, social and voluntary secto
defaultr care for health gain.
default&#xa0;
default2.3 As previously mentioned, 
defaulteye care services can be a lead area for QIPP, freeing up resources in the NHS, and delivering quality improvements at low cost. A very noteworthy innovation in eye care is the development of the Commis
defaultsioning Toolkit for Eye Care by the UK Vision Strategy. This toolkit highlights why eye care services should be prioritised, the potential for a small investment to deliver siz
defaulte
defaultable results, and provides guidance to support the commissioning of better eye 
defaultcare services across the NHS.
default 
defaultMoreover, the recently formed
default Clinical Council for Eye Health Commissioning 
defaultwill also aim
default to offer united, evidence-based clinical advice and guidance to those commissioning and delivering eye health services in England on is
defaultsues where national leadership is needed.
