default4default.) defaultReports of particular financial pressures in the system, such as funding for General Practice, and for Accident and Emergency servicesdefault4
default.1 
defaultUrgent eye care is provided by GPs, optometrists, A&amp;
defaultE departments, minor injury units, eye casualty departments and rapid-access outpatient clinics. An urgent eye condition is any eye condition that is of recent onset and is distressing or is believed by the patient, carer or referring health professional t
defaulto present an imminent threat to vision or general health. However many patients treated by the urgent eye care service have non-urgent conditions, particularly patients who self-refer to eye casualty. 
default4
default.2 
defaultMost hospital urgent eye care services report that
default they struggle to keep pace with demand. Demand for hospital eye emergency services is thought to be increasing. Evidence from London, shows that over a five year period up to 2011, demand at two major eye casualty units increased by seven and ten per cent
default year on year
default and eye emergencies are estimated to make up 1.46-6% of accident and emergency attendances
default. However, most urgent eye conditions are non-acute and relatively straightforward to treat
default. 
default4
default.3 
defaultTo make services more accessible and reduce pressur
defaulte on hospital eye casualty, a significant proportion of patients can be diagnosed and managed in a primary care instead by a healthcare professional with a slit lamp (which allows you to see the front and back of the eye in detail and is needed to diagnose
default most urgent eye conditions) and the skills and experience to use it. GPs do not usually have slit lamps or enough experience of using one, but community optometrists do and are
default 
defaultwell placed to promptly diagnose, triage and treat patients with urgent eye 
defaultpr
defaultoblems safely and efficiently.
default4
default.
default4
default 
defaultOther efficiencies could be made by nationwide adoption of 
defaulta number of successful enhanced eye care services, namely in glaucoma referral refinement, management of stable glaucoma, and primary eyecare assessment in 
defaultcommunity optical practices.  These tried and tested schemes have delivered better patient outcomes, local cost savings, reduced waiting times and helped to deliver a local patient-centred service without increasing patient risk.
default Adopting these schemes ha
defaults also freed up significant capacity in secondary eye care to focus on patients facing acute or chronic sight loss. 
